Concerned -<br>
Thanks for more clearly presenting what you were after in creating this discussion thread.  I apologize for presuming you had a particular agenda up your sleeve.  I read your initial post as one soliciting vets to tell how they'd been abused by &quot;the media&quot;, and I really don't think we'll get anywhere by finger-pointing (though I've certainly done some of that myself).<br>
I am curious about your facts.  Especially the one about suicides - I've seen much higher figures (in Marilyn Young's history The Vietnam Wars...).  How am I to judge which is accurate?  Seems like a tough to get at.  I can say that I don't know any vets who've done themselves in, but personal experience of one vet is hardly the basis for sweeping generalizations.<br>
I do wonder how and why the &quot;common knowledge&quot; you perceive to be false has come to be &quot;common knowledge&quot;?  Any thoughts?  And is it really common knowledge?  My experience with students shows mostly a profound ignorance about the war - after all it was SO LONG ago.  They don't seem to have a view of vietnam vets one way or the other.
<p><code>-- miketol@mtco.com  (Mike Toliver) </code><p>


